answer.step_by_step_thinking:
In examining the edentulous mouth of an aged patient wearing complete maxillary denture against six mandibular teeth, the dentist will likely observe changes in the osseous structure of the anterior maxilla where there would normally be natural teeth present but now only supported by a removable prosthesis. Therefore, flabby tissue in the posterior region does not align with what typically occurs given the presence of a well-fitting full denture, decrease interocclusal distance pertains to occlusion rather than structural change, and cystic degeneration of nerves is unrelated to bony resorption seen after tooth loss without replacement.
\boxed{\text{B}}
Given the context of an elderly patient who wears a complete maxillary denture over six remaining lower teeth, we expect to see some degree of resorption and subsequent reduction in osseous structure in the anterior maxilla because those areas do not receive support from underlying teeth anymore. Thus, the correct observation should reflect this alteration in bone density.

